\pard\f0\fs28 Dwarf plants, mainly from high altitudes, with greyish leaves bearing much longer hairs, have been described as var.{\i  palmata} (Lapeyr.) Engler & Irmscher, but it is possible that they are hybrids.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 92. S. moncayensis} D.A. Webb,{\i  Feddes Repert.}{\b  68}: 201 (1963). Leafy shoots long and very numerous, forming soft, fairly dense, deep cushions up to 150 cm across of light green, slightly scented foliage. Plant covered with very short glandular hairs (0·15-0·2 mm) giving a verruculose rather than pubescent appearance to the naked eye. Petiole 8-13 mm; lamina 8-11 × 9-15 mm, deeply divided into 3 primary lobes, which are narrowly oblong to oblanceolate, obtuse and deeply sulcate; the lateral lobes occasionally bear short secondary lobes. Flowering stem 5-10 cm, terminal; inflorescence with 3-7 primary branches, each bearing 3-5 flowers. Petals 6-7 mm, broadly oblong. Ovary almost inferior, surmounted by a bright yellow nectariferous disc. 2n = c. 60.{\i  Shady, siliceous rocks at} 1000-1600 {\i m. • Mountains of N.E. Spain.} Hs.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 93. S. vayredana} Luizet, {\i Bull. Soc. Bot. Fr.}{\b  60}: 413 (1913). Like {\b 92} but foliage with a much stronger spicy or balsamic scent; leaves somewhat smaller, and with 3-9 acute segments, which are not sulcate; panicle smaller and more compact, with not more than 9 flowers; petals obovate. 2n = c. 64. {\i Shady, siliceous rocks and screes, }700-1600 {\i m. N.E. Spain} ({\i Sierra de Montseny}). Hs.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 94. S. intricata} Lapeyr.,{\i  Fig. Fl. Pyr.} 58 (1801) ({\i S. nervosa} Lapeyr., {\i S. mixta} Lapeyr., pro parte). Stems woody; leafy shoots short, forming small tufts or cushions. Leaves rather rigid, darkish green, very shortly glandular-pubescent, with hairs as in{\b  92} and {\b 93}. Lamina 5-7 × 5-10 mm, with 3-5(-9) linear-oblong, obtuse, sulcate segments. Flowering stem 5-10 cm, bearing a panicle of 3-12 flowers. Petals 4-6 mm, broadly obovate to suborbicular, contiguous, patent, white. 2n = 34.{\i  Exposed, often dry, siliceous rocks. E. & C. Pyrenees; one station in the Cordillera Cantabrica.} Ga Hs.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 95. S. pentadactylis} Lapeyr.,{\i  op. cit.} 64 (1801). Glabrous; leaves, shoots, flowering stem and hypanthia covered with sessile glands and often viscid. Stems woody at the base; leafy shoots rather few, forming small cushions. Petiole usually longer than the lamina, which is divided to the base into 3 lobes, each further divided into 2 or 3 segments; segments 3-10 × 0·5-1·5 mm, linear to oblong, obtuse, sulcate. Flowering stem 7-17 cm, terminal, bearing 5-50 flowers. Petals 3·5-5 mm, obovate to oblong. Ovary inferior.{\i  Rocks, usually shady, but often dry, usually above }1800{\i  m. • E. Pyrenees and mountains of N. & C. Spain.} Ga Hs.
\par

